Big time.
Consumer end, you went from vinyl & cassettes at the beginning of the 80s to CDs at the end of the 90s. You went from the rawest blocky sprites of the Atari to the pseudo 3d of the 16bit consoles. You went from the 8086 to the PIII. In 1980, what counted as the internet was almost entirely universities/business. By 1999, AOL ads were everywhere and Joe Average was being told the every task in the future would be computerized.
>Fashion?
Slipped even further into the casual
>Music?
You went from the last gasp of the original punks & disco to a much more segregated black & white music scene. The 70s were peak inventiveness with regards to multitrack recording and emerging synth tech. The further you got from then the less interchange of ideas across genre boundaries.
Let's not forget MTV; in 1980, you had to either be a great live act or get played in dance clubs. In 1999, MTV said who you listened to.

Another way of looking at it
the 80s were an optimistic recession, and the 90s were a pessimistic boom time (especially near the end)
